coupled with conservation by business and consumers and falling natural gas=20
prices, have begun to tame the state's market.=20
Still, the state had to purchase $321 million in power in April and May,=20
about 10% more than Davis' analysts had projected.=20
Hidlago said that was because of hot weather in May and other supply problem=
s=20
in April. He said reports will show that power purchases fell short of state=
=20
projections in June and early July.=20
The reports also will show that prices paid by the state were down in June=20
and July, partly because spot prices have fallen sharply, often to well unde=
r=20
$100 a megawatt-hour.=20
A summary Department of Water Resources report released Monday credited=20
Davis' program of nurturing new power generation and establishing long-term=20
power contracts with with "moving the California electric energy industry=20
closer to normalcy."

